ddress a circular dependency problem. The user ran a test, but it seems we can’t see any output from the run. It looks like the `compileClasspath` is incorrectly set up because of how we're including `testImplementation`. This could be causing the test compile class to depend on bootstrap output, creating a circular dependency. I might need to adjust the `compileClasspath` to avoid using `sourceSets.test.compileClasspath`. I'll explore alternatives to keep this organized.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Resolving nativeTest issues**\\\\n\\\\nI’m looking at the `nativeTest` configuration. It seems that `tasks.named(\\\\\\\"test\\\\\\\")` isn’t having any effect on `nativeTest`, and there's a circular dependency likely because `nativeTest` depends on some classes. This might complicate things since `nativeTest` compiles tests to native instead of running them in the JVM. I also wonder about dynamic access reports potentially using `javaTest`. I need to ensure there's no circular reference and might need to edit `build.gradle` for clarity on how `nativeTest` should incorporate `bootstrapProbeClasses`.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Inspecting build.gradle**\\\\n\\\\nI need to take a closer look at `build.gradle` along with the TCK plugin's native task configurations. It’s crucial to review relevant sections to understand how tasks are set up. This should help me identify any potential issues or conflicts that might be affecting the build process. By examining these configurations, I hope to figure out the best way to resolve any outstanding problems. Let’s delve into the specifics and see what we uncover!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_GVbwTDNtbz08geJhTLeOXwfC|fc_053f396fbad82c020169f4dc8ab7a8819388c3ac69b9cd0fde\", \"name\": \"read\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/com.sun.xml.dtd-parser/dtd-parser/1.5.1/build.gradle\", \"limit\": 220}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 14642, \"output\": 545, \"cacheRead\": 28672, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 43859, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777654908379, \"responseId\": \"resp_053f396fbad82c020169f4dc7d660081938652dfb68058f158\"}, \"toolResults\": [{\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_GVbwTDNtbz08geJhTLeOXwfC|fc_053f396fbad82c020169f4dc8ab7a8819388c3ac69b9cd0fde\", \"toolName\": \"read\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\nplugins {\\n    id \\\"org.graalvm.internal.tck\\\"\\n}\\n\\nString libraryVersion = tck.testedLibraryVersion.get()\\n\\ndependencies {\\n    testImplementation \\\"com.sun.xml.dtd-parser:dtd-parser:$libraryVersion\\\"\\n    testImplementation 'org.assertj:assertj-core:3.22.0'\\n}\\n\\nsourceSets {\\n    bootstrapProbe {\\n        java.srcDir \\\"src/bootstrapProbe/java\\\"\\n        resources.srcDir \\\"src/bootstrapProbe/resources\\\"\\n        compileClasspath += sourceSets.test.compileClasspath\\n    }\\n}\\n\\ndependencies {\\n    testImplementation sourceSets.bootstrapProbe.output\\n}\\n\\ntasks.named(\\\"test\\\") {\\n    dependsOn tasks.named(\\\"bootstrapProbeClasses\\\")\\n    doFirst {\\n        File dtdParserJar = configurations.testRuntimeClasspath.files.find { File file ->\\n            file.name.startsWith(\\\"dtd-parser-\\\") && file.name.endsWith(\\\".jar\\\")\\n        }\\n        if (dtdParserJar == null) {\\n            throw new GradleException(\\\"Could not resolve dtd-parser runtime JAR\\\")\\n        }\\n        String bootClasspath = [\\n                sourceSets.bootstrapProbe.output.classesDirs.asPath,\\n                sourceSets.test.output.resourcesDir.absolutePath,\\n                dtdParserJar.absolutePath\\n        ].join(File.pathSeparator)\\n        jvmArgs \\\"-Xbootclasspath/a:${bootClasspath}\\\"\\n    }\\n}\\n\\ngraalvmNative {\\n    agent {\\n        defaultMode = \\\"conditional\\\"\\n        modes {\\n            conditional {\\n                userCodeFilterPath = \\\"user-code-filter.json\\\"\\n            }\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777654923062}]}\n4838:[thinking] I could completely avoid the build.gradle bootclasspath hack by using a custom class loader. I need to hit the getSystemResourceAsStream branch without defining a catalog in bootstrap. It seems the MessageCatalog code checks if the class loader is null, and that’s only true for bootstrap-loaded classes. I’m wondering if getClassLoader might be null in native images. For Class.forName coverage, it may be sufficient to have class resource bundles in the test classpath. Let's see how to handle this without triggering circular errors in native tests.\n4844:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Exploring custom class loaders**\\n\\nI could completely avoid the build.gradle bootclasspath hack by using a custom class loader. I need to hit the getSystemResourceAsStream branch without defining a catalog in bootstrap. It seems the MessageCatalog code checks if the class loader is null, and that’s only true for bootstrap-loaded classes. I’m wondering if getClassLoader might be null in native images. For Class.forName coverage, it may be sufficient to have class resource bundles in the test classpath. Let's see how to handle this without triggering circular errors in native tests.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_053f396fbad82c020169f4dc8cc85881938ff946ff2f91c1f5\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp9NyUAVFsRH5G9Wk1pTMLWty6GVtsfcUnO57MiETuH6JPgrXBSopX9vv8xDBn